  <discussion>When sterile, Ditrichum pusillum is morphologically very similar to D. ambiguum and D. tortuloides.  When sporophytes are present, the dense, fine, obliquely striate peristome teeth with weak papillae immediately distinguish D. pusillum from those two species, which have spiculose peristome teeth.  The spores of D. pusillum (10–19 µm) are also larger compared to those of D. ambiguum (6–11 µm) and D. tortuloides (9–13 µm).  A discussion of the relationships of D. pusillum with both D. ambiguum and D. tortuloides was given by R. R. Ireland and H. Robinson (2001).</discussion>
